@Laura Stratton
It depends on what you mean by a lookup. Consulting a dictionary or encyclopedia? Opening the Collected Works of Shakespeare or the Bible or looking at maps? Those are what I used to do before these went online and Googling one of my entries to verify the spelling seems a short step down from that. To get the correct spelling either that way or from a dictionary, you already have to be relatively close.

Googling a clue? In the early days that constituted research similar to exploring Encyclopedia Britannica, but now it just brings up "NYT Crossword Answer for ...." which seems like an end-run around using the Check Answer feature.

@Laura Stratton
OK, then my longest streak of that kind is probably a couple of months. Which I found boring. Because I love looking things up. I want these to be too hard to get them with no research. 

But I only googled a clue once, well before the streak, and was disappointed that it just gave the answer. Which was also boring.

@Laura Stratton
Actually, I'll take that back--I most love really chewy puzzles that take me hours to solve but where I am able to do so without any research. 

But I miss the rabbit holes I used to go down reading about the rivers in some Eastern European nation. Or dipping back into my Collected Works of Shakespeare.

@Laura Stratton
♥️

I just got back from DC last night. Stayed on capitol hill but avoided the mall in general, which has been one of my favorite areas in the past.

@Laura Stratton My longest was 271, and I have no plans to do better in my lifetime, or try. That’s good enough for me and it always will be. 
I count as a lookup any effort whatsoever to help find an answer from any source other than my mind and its jumble of contents.
However, should I take a break from doing the puzzle, and during that break just happen to stumble across something, that’s not a lookup. It’s just a contribution from life.

